nec tantum dulcia, quantum et ...] ‘and not so sweet as both clear and fit to mellow the harsh flavour of wine’. Virgil does not say that the honey is not sweet, but that its sweetness (which is assumed to be great) is even excelled by its other qualities. The Romans mixed honey with wine to form mulsum, a drink taken immediately before dinner, cf. Hor. Sat. 2. 4. 24.
